4 SYNOPSIS:
5 Under existing law, a state resident who is
6 totally and permanently disabled and receives
7 disability benefits from certain entities may be issued
8 an annual special hunting or fishing license from the
9 Department of Conservation and Natural Resources for a
10 reduced fee.
11 This bill would establish lifetime special
12 hunting and fishing licenses for state residents who
13 are totally and permanently disabled.
14
15
16 A BILL
17 TO BE ENTITLED
18 AN ACT
19
20 Relating to the Department of Conservation and Natural
21 Resources; to add Section 9-11-54.1 to the Code of Alabama
22 1975, to establish lifetime disabled state resident special
23 hunting and fishing licenses.
24 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
25 Section 1. Section 9-11-54.1 is added to the Code of
26 Alabama 1975, to read as follows:
27 §9-11-54.1
28 (a) Beginning with the 2026 license year, an individual
Page 1

(a) Beginning with the 2026 license year, an individual
HB271 INTRODUCED
29 eligible to be issued an annual license under Section 9-11-54
30 shall be issued a lifetime license in lieu of an annual
31 license upon application and payment of a fee to the
32 Department of Conservation and Natural Resources as follows:
33 (1)a. Lifetime Disabled Resident Hunting License.
34 1. Individuals who are less than 50 years of age shall
35 be charged forty-five dollars ($45) for a lifetime disabled
36 resident hunting license.
37 2. Individuals who are 50 years of age or older shall
38 be charged twenty-five dollars ($25) for a lifetime disabled
39 resident hunting license.
40 b. Fees collected pursuant to this subdivision shall be
41 deposited into the Alabama Game and Fish Endowment Fund.
42 (2)a. Lifetime Disabled Freshwater Fishing License.
43 1. Individuals who are less than 50 years of age shall
44 be charged forty-five dollars ($45) for a lifetime disabled
45 resident freshwater fishing license.
46 2. Individuals who are 50 years of age or older shall
47 be charged twenty-five dollars ($25) for a lifetime disabled
48 resident freshwater fishing license.
49 b. Fees collected pursuant to this subdivision shall be
50 deposited into the Alabama Game and Fish Endowment Fund.
51 (3)a. Lifetime Disabled Resident Saltwater Fishing
52 License.
53 1. Individuals who are less than 50 years of age shall
54 be charged forty-five dollars ($45) for a lifetime disabled
55 resident saltwater fishing license.
56 2. Individuals who are 50 years of age or older shall
Page 2

2. Individuals who are 50 years of age or older shall
HB271 INTRODUCED
57 be charged twenty-five dollars ($25) for a lifetime disabled
58 resident saltwater fishing license.
59 b. Fees collected pursuant to this subdivision shall be
60 deposited into the Alabama Marine Resources Endowment Fund.
61 (b) The department may charge an issuance fee of one
62 dollar ($1) for a license, including a combination of
63 licenses, issued pursuant to this section.
64 (c) The fees provided in this section are subject to
65 adjustment pursuant to Sections 9-11-68 and 9-11-69.
66 (d) Applications for a license pursuant to this section
67 shall be filed in the office of the Commissioner of the
68 Department of Conservation and Natural Resources, or as
69 otherwise authorized by the commissioner, on forms prescribed
70 by the commissioner.
71 (e) A license issued pursuant to this section is not
72 transferable.
73 (f) A holder of a valid lifetime disabled resident
74 hunting or freshwater fishing license shall be entitled to all
75 of the privileges of a wildlife heritage license.
76 Section 2. This act shall become effective on October
77 1, 2026.
